2 years ago this little Porta-Viking made his entrance/exit to our world. In 2013, (after a vasectomy and 2 failed reversals) I was told that I had ZERO motile sperm.  Not low, but zero.  Wolf was an IVF baby and after the hurricane that he had been, we were taking a few before talking about having another child.  Honestly, I don’t know if I’d ever be ready but knowing that due to my situation (and the fact we have 3 healthy embryos on ice in Reno) I’d have a say on when that would happen. One would think…….Our little quarantine Miracle came along and has filled our lives with so much joy, laughs and love that we couldn’t be more thankful and grateful for how unscripted our lives have become.  Happiest of birthdays little Magnus Leif Demmel. This world will hear you.

Might be my favorite picture of us, ever.  Taken by @jessica_t_chase at the @vio_lence_band at the @oakland_metro a few weeks ago.  Without a full band rehearsal we seemed to pull together one of our tightest shows and a very supportive crowd helped us celebrate 35 years of our debut release “Eternal Nightmare”. At the show I thanked those who helped make it possible. Among them original members Troy Fua, Jerry Birr and Eddie Billy who along with Perry Strickland brought me into a band called Death Penalty my senior year of high school.  Perry changed our name to Violence and we soon added Deen Dell who injected the band with a live identity and energy. Without Deen I don’t think we would become the live force that we were.  Bringing in Sean next was the driving force to get things done.  He pushed us to write new tunes and booked our time at Prairie Sun to record the demo.  I remember leaving the Slayer RIB show in SF hammered in my parents van (with Eric and Chuck from Testament with me) to do a late night mix.  Sean pushed us to be better. Bringing in Robb was the final piece.  I had written most the record before he joined but he gave us a different view of music and writing. He wrote what would become “Calling in the Coroner” (after we aborted an attempt to use the music from forbidden’s Chalice of Blood) and he and I collaborated on Torture Tactics and would be pulled from EN and later pulled from Oppressing the masses. He made me want to be a better guitar player. Such precise and unique style.  Managed by Debbie Abono and Joey Huston.  Signed by Steve Sinclair. Artwork by Ed Repka (we see your tats all over the world), recorded, mixed by John Cuniberti, pics by Mark Leialoha, championed by Steffan Chirazi, hosted by Big Bob Corona and Freddy at the Stone SF.  Most of all, thanks to our FANS who love this band so much.  I’m probably missing a bunch and I apologize in advance.  This is late in posting but after 35 years, what’s a couple more weeks?  THANK ALL OF YOU FOR MAKING THIS ALBUM POSSIBLE!! 🖤🖤🖤

On a pizza Sunday 7 years ago, Wolf Aèquitas Demmel declared himself ready to make his appearance. After some complications, a C-section was necessary and he was delivered glowing blue and not making a sound for a few minutes.  As Marta was being treated and a bit out of it, I watched as they worked on our little boy.  It was the most most vulnerable and scared I’ve ever felt  But the he made himself heard shortly after and anyone within earshot has heard him since. He has brought so much energy into our lives and his loving and caring nature is unmatched.  We love you Wolf and hope you enjoy your day as much as we enjoy being yours. 🖤🖤🖤🐺🐺🐺

In between the home project madness and some recording, I’ve been woodshedding an iconic solo and have broken Michael out of his slumber.  @mikemfshannon worked on these and were done in time for one our runs with @metallica in 2009. Back to working on this solo that I should’ve learned years ago.  @waynelozinak evidently can play it so guess I need to raise my game. 🤘🏻🤘🏻 @bmcd1972 needs a shout out for making both of these happen!  Thanks, Brian!!!

One of the few pics I took at the final Slayer show 4 years ago.  I felt socially responsible to all my female (and some male) acquaintances to take this given my proximity to 2 of the most lusted-over dudes in the world.  As far the show, I took it all in including a trip through pit for raining blood with my reading glasses on my head surviving the trip. Slayer we’re the reason I decided to play heavy music instead of a more commercial direction in high school. They will always be held in the highest regard as far as my musical journey is concerned.  They also reassured this 50+ year old still had gas on his tank and was worthy of so many more things.  Thank you Kerry, Tom, Paul, Gary, Dave and Jeff for everything.

They are the reason.  Most bands have had their cringe-y moments, they are not exempt from that.  But they always will live in my musical soul as ground zero for the “why”. Full ramblings forthcoming live.  Pics from my 5th grade talent show, 1978
